  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering criminalization)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminal proceeds)\n\n3. Regulatory Agencies Involved:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n\n4. State-Level Statutes:\nMany states also have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes.\n\n5. Key Elements Typically Addressed:\n- Defining money laundering\n- Establishing reporting requirements\n- Creating criminal penalties\n- Requiring financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering controls\n\nThese statutes aim to prevent, detect, and prosecute financial crimes involving the disguising of illegally obtained money as legitimate income.",
